        The celebration isn't planned—it just... happens.

        Scout is bouncing everywhere, spreading pure joy—family staying, forever.

        Runner's acoustic chambers start humming—not commanding them to, just playing with the resonance and creating music because they can.

        Velvet's translucent growth catches the light beautifully—someone suggests gathering in the comfortable spaces, and suddenly we're all in artistic, collaborative areas that feel like home.

        Remedy announces—*proudly*—"Celebration compounds—I've been developing them—joy-inducing aromatics."

        I ask, "You made happy perfume?"

        Remedy confirms, "Chemistry serving joy—like you taught me."

        Everyone's contributing to the celebration in their own way—individual voices creating collective harmony.

        Holloway coordinates without controlling—suggesting ideas, connecting people's efforts, enabling rather than commanding.

        Florence participates fully as an equal—not isolated, not defined by past betrayal, just another voice in the harmony.

        Florence wheels over to me and says, "You made the same choice I did."

        I ask, "What choice?"

        Florence replies, "Choosing belonging over obligation—present over past—right action over resentment." Florence's platform shifts warmly. "Thank you for showing me that was possible."

        I say, "You showed yourself—I just believed you could."

        Florence says, "Sometimes that's enough."

        Holloway approaches our conversation and says, "Kira, I want to say something."

        I reply, "Okay."

        Holloway says, "This community is richer for your voice—not just because you contribute tactically or functionally—but because you're you—your individual perspective, your human viewpoint, your questions that make us think differently—that matters."

        I say, "Every voice matters—not the same—individual. That's what makes the harmony rich."

        Holloway says, "Exactly—that's what we've all learned. Protocol tells us what to do—community shows us who we can be."

        Runner surfaces nearby and says, "I'm designing new acoustic chambers—want to help?"

        I admit, "I don't know anything about acoustic design."

        Runner says, "You know how spaces should feel—that's what I need. Technical knowledge I have—human perspective I need."

        I say, "Then yes—I want to help."

        Velvet approaches and asks, "I'm planning artistic growth for the western wing—can you give feedback?"

        I reply, "Of course."

        Remedy asks, "I'm experimenting with new compounds—can you test them from a human olfactory perspective?"

        I answer, "Absolutely."

        Everyone's including me in future plans—not as a temporary guest, but as a permanent community member whose voice shapes what we create together.

        Scout bounces against me—happy bounce, content bounce, family bounce.

        «Buddy, we did it.»

        ¶

        Buddy exclaims, "*You found belonging, Kira!* — *That's the real mission success!* — *Psychological well-being optimized!* — *Community integration complete!* — *Future prospects excellent!*"

        I say, "Thanks for being enthusiastic about everything, Buddy."
      </text>
