        Scout exclaims— "That's my function! And also my genuine response! This is wonderful!"

        The celebration continues into evening, and plans emerge organically—next construction projects, Runner's acoustic designs, Velvet's artistic spaces, Remedy's experiments, collaborative efforts that incorporate everyone's unique contributions, including mine.

        Florence describes potential defensive improvements—not because we need them now, but because tactical thinking is her contribution, and everyone values it.

        Holloway coordinates future resource management with characteristic, enabling leadership.

        Scout moves between us, offering affection and social connection—their function, perfectly executed.

        And me? I'm contributing a human perspective to every discussion—my voice matters here, not instead of plant voices but alongside them, creating something richer together than any of us could create alone.

        The sun sets. Holloway's bioluminescence provides comfortable light; Velvet's growth frames the spaces beautifully; Remedy's scents make everything pleasant; Runner's acoustic chambers hum gentle harmonics.

        Scout curls up against me, exhausted from celebration bouncing—content, peaceful, family bounce.

        I look around at everyone: these weird, wonderful bureaucratic alien plants who somehow created the most authentic human community I've ever experienced, because they value individual voices, including mine.

        I say quietly— "Home isn't where you're from. It's where your voice matters. Where you contribute uniquely to something larger. Where being different makes the harmony richer instead of making you unwelcome."

        Everyone's listening.

        I continue— "That's what I've learned here. Individual voices create better harmony than any protocol could design. Not despite our differences. Because of them."

        Holloway replies warmly— "That's what we've all learned. You taught us as much as we taught you."

        Florence adds— "We transformed together."

        Runner says— "Individual voices."

        Velvet finishes— "Creating collective harmony."

        Remedy contributes— "That's better than protocol."

        Scout bounces in agreement.

        The facility settles into a comfortable evening quiet—everyone resting, recovering from celebration, planning futures together. I'm part of those futures now, not temporarily, not conditionally—permanently.

        ¶

        This is home. These weird bureaucratic alien plants are my family. This transformed facility—acoustic chambers that sing, artistic growth that glows, enhancement scents that please, collaborative spaces that comfort—this is where I belong, where my individual voice contributes to collective harmony, where differences create richness instead of division, where belonging transcends species because what matters is valuing each other authentically.

        Scout makes a sleepy, happy bounce—perfect day bounce, family bounce, home bounce.

        I whisper to them— "Yeah. Home."
